{"type":"message","id":"bd5cf0b8","parentId":"f7af57db","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:38:42.388Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jxnniu2pzf5h_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 103816\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what action to take.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n- CFI analysis is done showing 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7) which are true causal anchors\r\n- Pending tasks include:\r\n  - CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n  - Implement CFI filtering\r\n  - Distinguish constant format from research trajectory\r\n  - Wire to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  - Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe most immediate next step based on the findings is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The notes say \"Next: CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare vs frequency baseline)\"\r\n\r\nI need to design and implement this experiment. Let me think about what this involves:\r\n\r\n1. Take the invariants data (frequency counts)\r\n2. Apply CFI weighting to filter/compress\r\n3. Compare next-pulse prediction quality vs frequency baseline\r\n\r\nThe CFI_RESULTS.md should have the data I need. Let me look at what data is available and design the experiment.\r\n\r\nFor a concrete action, I should create an experiment design document or start implementing the CFI-weighted compression script.\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete file that advances this - either a script or an experiment design that can be executed.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis reveals that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) and only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7). This suggests frequency-only compression loses significant signal, and CFI-weighted compression should improve next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a CFI-weighted compression experiment script that tests whether filtering invariants by CFI threshold improves next-pulse prediction compared to the frequency baseline. This directly addresses the pending \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\" task.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression (filtering invariants by CFI threshold) will yield better next-pulse prediction than frequency-only compression.\r\n\r\n## Method\r\n1. **Baseline**: Top-K invariants by frequency (current approach)\r\n2. **CFI-Weighted**: Top-K invariants by frequency, then filter by CFI threshold >= 0.7\r\n3. **Compare**: Both approaches tested against same pulse history\r\n\r\n## Invariants Source\r\nFrom `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`:\r\n- 44.8% of invariants: CFI=0 (noise/metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n- 5.7% of invariants: CFI>=0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI: 0.181\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n- Baseline (freq-only): Includes ~45% noise invariants\r\n- CFI-weighted: Filters noise, keeps causal trajectory\r\n\r\n## Implementation Notes\r\n- Use same corpus as frequency baseline\r\n- Compare prediction accuracy, not just compression ratio\r\n- Consider hybrid: (freq * CFI) scoring\r\n\"\r\nfile: experiments/cfi_compression_experiment.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:38:36\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774363122387}}
